<div class="row">
  <div class="col-md-12">
    <h1>New Container - Step 2</h1>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="row">
  <div class="col-md-12">
    <form method="POST" enctype="multipart/form-data" class="form-horizontal">
      <fieldset>
        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-md-6">
            <legend>Domain</legend>
            <div class="row">
              <label class="control-label col-md-2" for="hostname">Domain:</label>
              <div class="col-md-10">
                <input type="text" class="form-control" id="hostname" name="hostname" placeholder="Domain..." value="{{hostname}}">
                <span class="help-block">
                  The is different from the containers name, and should be a domain that you own. Once you finish getting your new container spun up, you'll recieve instructions on how to point your domain at it.
                </span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="col-md-6">
            <legend>Ports</legend>
            <p>You can choose to route http traffic (and only http traffic) to a given port within the container. If you don't specify a port, then you can use the automatically generated ports on the right.</p>
            {% for port in ports %}
              <div class="row">
                <div class="col-md-12">
                  <label class="sr-only" for="host">Host:</label>
                  <div class="input-group">
                    <span class="input-group-addon">{{port}}</span>
                    <input class="form-control" type="text" name="port_{{port}}" placeholder="Host Port">
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <br>
            {% endfor %}
          </div>
        </div>
      </fieldset>
      <button class="btn btn-theme pull-right" type="submit">Spin up! <i class="fa fa-check"></i></button>
    </form>
  </div>
</div>
